      "date": "2012-07-10 06:27:12.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1: Verified\n\nTests received by maloo, run on CentOS release 6.2/x86_64, CentOS release 5.8/x86_64: (https://maloo.whamcloud.com/test_sessions/738777d0-ca55-11e1-a9ff-52540035b04c).  Ran 12 tests.  No failures.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "f35301272afa68ab6211c57b2202f06850e4f6b2",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2012-08-09 22:19:09.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nCan someone please inspect this simple patch, it has been waiting for a month now.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "c9510f53c9f66835a0104c6f55acbf42d60f9f11",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 257,
        "name": "Keith Mannthey",
        "email": "keith.mannthey@intel.com",
        "username": "kmannth",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2012-08-10 00:23:16.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nSorry I don't know enough about our git system to say yea or nay.  build/commit.ok_diffinside just looks like a 2nd commit message to me and I don't understand how it adds a test case.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "11c3d29018125744d8ce156966aed441fe00a23d",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 221,
        "name": "Bruce Korb",
        "email": "bruce_korb@xyratex.com",
        "username": "bkorb",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2012-08-10 01:36:35.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1: Looks good to me, but someone else must approve\n\nNote to Keith:\n\nThis is strictly a test message verifying that, when used and processed by commit-msg script, it is seen as okay and the entire message is passed through to GIT.  To understand its usage, you have to look at the Makefile to see that test-commit-msg.sh gets run and uses all files named commit.*.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "f06d614139fbc47a394034e18749e3d7a4d30a33",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2012-08-10 01:52:28.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nKeith, in the build/ subdirectory are the git commit hooks that validate the commit message and code style. There is a Makefile target to test the commit-msg script, \"make check-commit\" IIRC that runs the script against all of the commit.* files, and files named commit.ok_* should pass the commit-msg script, while other commit.* files should fail the check.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "dbb7151e7f9c4b8a4b43a907a3fab6981aa75e6b",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 131,
        "name": "Jian Yu",
        "email": "yujian@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "yujian"
      },
      "date": "2012-08-10 13:47:02.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1: Looks good to me, but someone else must approve\n\n",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
